12/ Overall, I see an incredible opportunity within the DAO tooling and infrastructure space.  Iâ€™m still learning about web3 and would love to connect with others investing & building in this space.ğŸš€Let me know if you have any thoughts / feedback.ğŸ™ https://t.co/1hChg6a1cS

11/ LEGAL: Unlike corporations, DAOs donâ€™t fit cleanly into existing regulatory frameworks. Tools that help manage legal and tax nuances around 1) member protection from liabilities, 2) tax treatment for DAO-related activities, & 3) compliance are critical for mainstream adoption

10/ Can we convert on-chain activity into a web3 version of a resume and credentials that can be ported across DAOs? This type of on-chain reputation system will allow members to showcase their contributions, governance voting history, and token holdings to other DAOs they join.

9/ REPUTATION: Traditionally, resumes allow companies to get a glimpse of an individualâ€™s skills & experiences, but that doesnâ€™t exist in web3. There are no accurate tools for determining who to trust and collaborate with, thus difficult to align with members with similar beliefs

8/ CONTRIBUTION: Currently, 1% of DAO members do 90% of the work. Tools that can turn disengaged members into active contributors will help retain top talent and create meaningful value. How can we distribute responsibilities to members while tracking their progress via KPIs?

7/ COORDINATION: Are there tools to find and assign specific tasks to members based on their on-chain activity? What are some project management, documentation, and workflow tools that can help web3 organizations stay on track, self-organize, and better coordinate?

6/ COORDINATION: Symmetrical information is critical for DAOs, but thereâ€™s currently no clear way for the latest announcements & priorities to be seamlessly shared with members. DAO coordination at scale is challenging because â€œworkâ€ has historically been driven by hierarchy.

5/ ONBOARDING: After joining a Discord, members are unsure who to connect with and become overwhelmed with the experience. DAO tools that support clear onboarding processes (e.g. apprenticeships, bounties, working groups) and workflows will improve retention and contribution.

4/ ONBOARDING: Most DAOs are doing a sub-par job of getting new members involved, leading to a leaky funnel. In traditional orgs, there are processes for new employees to set up 1-1s with functional peers or be assigned to an onboarding buddy. The same does not exist within DAOs.

3/ And this is why many web2 tools (e.g., Slack, GoogleDocs, Asana) cannot be retrofitted to this new way of self-organization. Even with $9B+ in AUM and $21B total market cap of DAO tokens today, these web3 orgs are still lacking the right tools to coordinate effectively.

2/ There needs to be a shift in how we work together in a hierarchal model to this new decentralized world. As such, DAOs must reverse engineer years of â€œbest practicesâ€ from traditional governance and leverage a new tech stack that embodies crypto-native organizational thinking.

DAOs are transforming how organizations invest, govern, collaborate, and participate in this #web3 paradigm. Iâ€™ve highlighted a few pain points #DAOs experience today and mapped out areas of opportunity for crypto-native tools and infrastructure to better support DAOs. ğŸ‘‡ https://t.co/x7Up9liCEo
